<paper id="233279079"><title>Universal Re-encryption for Mixnets</title><year>2004</year><authors><author org="Stanford, University" id="2014852109">Philippe Golle</author><author org="RSA Laboratories" id="2057643108">Markus Jakobsson</author><author org="RSA Laboratories" id="46726047">Ari Juels</author><author org="Naval Research Laboratory" id="2051205022">Paul F. Syverson</author></authors><n_citation>352</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1494929562</reference><reference>1495266644</reference><reference>1523373677</reference><reference>1532961226</reference><reference>1594645505</reference><reference>1850322980</reference><reference>1878594160</reference><reference>1913505164</reference><reference>1932868796</reference><reference>2020805258</reference><reference>2095708839</reference><reference>2101770573</reference><reference>2103647628</reference><reference>2106583429</reference><reference>2108834246</reference><reference>2110740499</reference><reference>2128735745</reference><reference>2144820675</reference><reference>2167654758</reference><reference>2405015683</reference><reference>2471061660</reference></references><venue id="2760694600" type="C">The Cryptographers’ Track at the RSA Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-24660-2_14</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.72387">Cramer–Shoup cryptosystem</keyword><keyword weight="0.4331">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.53225">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.42221">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.6283">Cryptosystem</keyword><keyword weight="0.55327">Encryption</keyword><keyword weight="0.43385">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.45278">Anonymity</keyword><keyword weight="0.57724">Ciphertext</keyword><keyword weight="0.68597">ElGamal encryption</keyword><keyword weight="0.60298">Public-key cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.41793">Distributed computing</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We introduce a new cryptographic technique that we call universal re-encryption. A conventional cryptosystem that permits re-encryption, such as ElGamal, does so only for a player with knowledge of the public key corresponding to a given ciphertext. In contrast, universal re-encryption can be done without knowledge of public keys. We propose an asymmetric cryptosystem with universal re-encryption that is half as efficient as standard ElGamal in terms of computation and storage.</abstract></paper>